      "created_at" : "Tue Apr 28 13:49:24 +0000 2026",
      "text" : "as a CEO steering tool, \"the norm by May 2026 will be launching one simulation per day\"\n\nsharing a cool overview of @miroshark_ 🦈\n\nthe main bits:\n> he switched to MiroShark bc of a struggle with MiroFish (bugs, 500 errors, an 8-round skip in a 60-round simulation)\n> ran a full relaunch on MiroShark w/ Qwen 3-235B - , fast simulation (~20 min for 40 rounds, 678 events, 0 errors)\n> structured report with verdict, confidence score (failure at 87%), top 5 emerging dynamics, and the ability to chat with individual or grouped agents.\n\ninteresting insights:\n> data sovereignty: everything runs locally via Neo4j, nothing passes through ZepCloud anymore — critical for CEOs feeding sensitive internal processes into the system.\n> zero errors across 678 events vs 120 errors/hour on MirrorFish, largely thanks to an OpenRouter fallback system that retries automatically.\n> deepSeek V4 Pro over-reasons for this kind of massively parallel task; Qwen 3-235B is the right speed/quality trade-off for swarm work.\n> unbeatable cost/result ratio: ~20 minutes and a few cents to produce a dataset that weeks of focus groups couldn't generate.\n> using director mode to inject chaos mid-simulation (e.g., \"the CTO resigns\") to stress-test organizational resilience — the business equivalent of chaos engineering.\n> counterfactual branches (forking a simulation at round N to inject an alternative narrative) — a concept close to \"git for strategic decisions,\" virtually nonexistent in mainstream tools.\n\nand the most insightful part imo:\n> native Polymarket integration inside a business simulation (not just crypto) — the creator himself openly wonders whether it adds signal or noise, and invites debate. A genuinely open question.\n> the concept of \"informal silo recreation\": the simulation surfaced \"ghost guilds\" — Slack channels created by influential engineers that quietly rebuild the old silos in new clothing. A real phenomenon in companies, rarely modeled.\n> The invisible hierarchy inversion detected by the simulation: officially retained \"chapter leads\" become phantom figures while self-proclaimed \"squad leads\" capture real power.\n> CEOs aren't looking for a \"best answer\" but for an enriched dataset that exposes blind spots which would otherwise take a year of customer conversations to surface.\n\nreally sharp analysis, thanks for your time on this @meydeey 🙏"
