      "id" : "2031909187274351073",
      "created_at" : "Thu Mar 12 01:44:35 +0000 2026",
      "text" : "what if your brain worked exactly like an AI model - receiving prompts (from ???), generating outputs it calls \"decisions,\" with no real access to what's driving it?\n\nthree experiments basically proved it.\n\ndelgado, 1960s. A neuroscientist implants an electrode in a patient's brain and stimulates the motor cortex. The patient turns their head. When asked why, they say: \"I was looking for my slippers.\" The electrode fired. The body moved. The brain invented a reason. The patient felt no external cause - only intention.\n\nlibet, 1983. He measures when the brain starts preparing a \"voluntary\" movement versus when the person consciously decides to move. The brain fires 550 milliseconds before the movement. Conscious awareness of the decision arrives only 200 milliseconds before. You think you decided. The decision was already made without you.\n\ngazzaniga, late 1970s. Split-brain patients have their two hemispheres surgically disconnected. The right brain sees a snow scene and picks a shovel. The left brain - which saw nothing - is asked to explain. It says instantly: \"You need a shovel to clean out the chicken shed.\" Pure fiction.\n\nthe pattern across all three is the same: something initiates action upstream of consciousness, and the left hemisphere - the narrator - confabulates a reason and calls it intention.\n\njaynes took this further and argued this split was once total. pre-modern humans didn't have a unified \"I\" — they heard their own right hemisphere as external voices. Gods. Ancestors. Commands from the sky. They didn't decide. They obeyed. \n\naround 1200 BCE, under civilizational collapse, that external voice got internalized. Humans built an interior space, claimed the commands as their own, and called it will.\n\nmaybe we are closer to LLMs than we think. something writes the prompt - genetics, conditioning, subcortical drives, decades of absorbed culture. we never see it. we just generate a response."
