      "text" : "this paper is fucking wild: scientists put a helmet on a cockroach and turned it into a remote-controlled cyborg\n\n> they built a 0.1g 3D-printed helmet with UV LEDs positioned over each compound eye. Cockroaches naturally flee UV light - so flashing the left eye makes it turn right, and vice versa.\n\n\"Targeted stimulation of the compound eyes results in directional turning behaviors such as left eye stimulation-induced right-turning and right eye stimulation-induced left-turning\"\n\n> the key insight vs previous cyborg insects: no surgery, no wire implants, no removing antennae. They work with the insect's sensory system instead of bypassing it. An IMU detects when the cockroach stops moving - only then does UV fire. 81% of movement was the cockroach navigating on its own.\n\n\"Unlike electrical stimulation, which often leads to habituation and reduced responsiveness over time, UV stimulation maintains consistent efficacy\"\n\n> Electrical stim cockroaches stopped responding after ~60 trials. UV cockroaches were still going at 150+. 94% escape rate in complex terrain with rocks, walls, and food distractions.\n\nthey call it a \"bio-intelligent cyborg insect\" - the cockroach's brain still makes decisions, the system just nudges perception.\n\nwho up controlling their cockroach?"
