      "created_at" : "Fri Jan 23 16:01:20 +0000 2026",
      "text" : "The Less-Efficient Market Hypothesis - fascinating paper\n\nthesis: over the last 30 years, stock markets have gotten worse at pricing reality\n\n- \"A well-functioning free enterprise system needs a well-functioning capital market... the prices accorded to enterprises, be they very high or very low, provide direct incentives for how society allocates its resources\"\n\nbroken prices = broken capital allocation\n\n- \"Availability of data has never been what's hardest about investing. It's rational processing of information that is dear.\"\n\n- \"I think the people who assume technological advances must've made the market more efficient are the same people who assume social media must've made us all like each other more!\"\n\ncore idea: wisdom of crowds requires independence\n\n- \"What if the crowd isn't independent, but acts in unison? Well, this has the potential not just to destroy the magical crowd wisdom but to turn it into a negative.\"\n\nand then\n\n- \"has there ever been a better vehicle for turning a wise, independent crowd into a coordinated clueless even dangerous mob than social media?\"\n\nhis description of modern trading is brutal:\n\n- \"Instantaneous, gamified, cheap, 24-hour trading on your smartphone after getting all your biases reinforced by exhortations on social media from randos and grifters with vaguely NSFW pseudonyms filtered and delivered to you by algorithms which famously push people to further and further extremes\"\n\nWhat could possibly go wrong?\n\nhe compares it to gambling addiction:\n\n- \"imagine video poker where the odds were in your favor... This form of video poker would laugh at crack cocaine as the ultimate addiction. In my view, this is precisely what on-line trading has become\"\n\nBuffett quote he includes:\n\n- \"markets now exhibit far more casino-like behavior than they did when I was young. The casino now resides in many homes and daily tempts the occupants\"\n\nthe data backs it up - value spreads (gap between expensive/cheap stocks) hit 50-year extremes TWICE in just 20 years\n\nmispricings that used to self-correct in months now persist for a decade\n\nso if stock markets are failing at information aggregation... what fills the gap?\n\nmaybe prediction markets\n\nforced resolution dates. clear binary outcomes.\n\nstock prices aggregate information as a byproduct. prediction markets do it as the core function.\n\nmaybe the gamification isn't a bug to fight - it's infrastructure for a new information layer native to how gen z actually processes the world"
